How to Increment the Counter (The Hardware Action)
To see those 0s change to 1s, you need to create a Falling Edge—an electrical transition from 3.3V (High) to 0V (Low).

1. The Physical Wiring
Since we configured the pin with IRQF_TRIGGER_FALLING:

Identify Physical Pin 11 (which is BCM 17).

Identify any Ground Pin (like Physical Pin 9, 14, or 25).

The Action: Take a jumper wire, plug one end into Pin 11, and tap the other end against a Ground pin.

2. Why it increments
When the wire touches Ground:

The voltage on BCM 17 drops to 0V.

the pinctrl-bcm2835 hardware detects this "Falling Edge."

The hardware sends a signal to the CPU's Interrupt Controller (GIC).

The Kernel pauses the current task and jumps to your gpio_irq_handler function.

The Kernel increments the counter in /proc/interrupts for the CPU core that handled the event.

Verification Steps
Monitor in real-time:
Run this in a terminal to watch the count jump as you touch the wire:

Bash
watch -n 0.1 "cat /proc/interrupts | grep pi_irq_handler"
